The `--hmr` or `--watch-hmr` don't work well with Lume because it gives no control over the changed files. At least this was my feeling the last time I checked them. This feature only watches the JS/TS files loaded by Deno and tries to upgrade the modules automatically or restart the entire process. This can work well with Fresh, but Lume need to watch other files that are not ES modules loaded by Deno (like assets, markdown files, vto templates, etc) and the process to apply the changes is a bit more complex.

Maybe it could help if Deno triggered an event that Lume could listen in order to have more control. Something like:

```js
addEventListener("filechanged", (ev) => {
  const { filename, canHotReload } = ev.details;
  if (canHotReload) {
    console.log(`The file ${filename} was changed and can be hot reloaded`);
    Deno.hotReload(filename); // Hot reload the file
  } else {
    console.log(`The file ${filename} was changed and cannot be hot reloaded. Restarting process...`);
    Deno.restart();
  }
});
```

Or even without events, just a simple API that Lume can use:

```js
if (Deno.canHotReload(changedFile) {
  Deno.hotReload(changedFile);
} else {
  // Other methods.
}
```

As a workaround, adding this to `_config.ts` works:

```ts
import { stop } from "lume/deps/esbuild.ts"

const isWatch = Deno.args.some((arg) => ["-s", "--serve", "-w", "--watch"].includes(arg))
if (!isWatch) addEventListener("lume:afterBuild", stop)
```

