Comments.Body:
Hi! It's a really interesting topic and, honesty, I never had thought about it before.

My first idea was, as you have suggested, implement this as a markdown plugin. Lume has some specific markdown plugins that you can install like `toc` that extract the table of contents and save it in a [property in the page data](https://github.com/lumeland/markdown-plugins/blob/main/toc/mod.ts#L120-L127). This allows to render it in the layout [using the html you want](https://github.com/lumeland/markdown-plugins/blob/main/toc/demo/_includes/default.vto#L12).

But that doesn't work in this case because backlinks need to render all pages before rendering the layouts, and `renderOrder` can break this (as you noticed). The proposal of rendering the layouts after all pages content are rendered looks good. Interestingly enough, I'm working on a new major version (Lume v3) that I was planing to release the next week. I can test this solution to make sure it doesn't break anything.

Another option is to use preprocessors (the Lume approach for computedData). Preprocessors are functions that you can run before the pages are rendered. You can use them to change the page data. For example:

```js
site.preprocess([".md"], (pages) => {
    for (const page of pages) {
      const links = searchLinksInMarkdown(page.data.url, page.data.content);

      for (const link of links) {
        const linkedPage = pages.find((page) => page.data.url === link);
        linkedPage.data.backlinks ??= [];
        linkedPage.data.backlinks.push(page);
      }
    }
});
```

I didn't test it but you get an idea. Now all pages have a `backlinks` property which is an array of other pages linked to it.
The drawback of this solution is the markdown must be rendered twice, first to search the links in the preprocessor, and then to render the page. Markdown rendering is a fast operation so maybe it's not a problem.


And another option is to use processors (like preprocessors but when all pages are already rendered). Processors allow to use the DOM API so it's easy to search for links:

```js
site.process([".html"], (pages) => {
  for (const page of pages) {
    const links = page.document.querySelectorAll(".content a");
    for (const link of links) {
      const resolved = resolve(page.url, link.getAttribute("href"));
      const linkedPage = pages.find((page) => page.data.url === resolved);
      linkedPage.data.backlinks ??= [];
      linkedPage.data.backlinks.push(page);
    }
  }

  // Now, render the backlinks of evey page
  for (const page of pages) {
    const { backlinks } = page.data;
    if (backlinks) {
      const container = page.document.querySelector(".backlinks");
      container.innerHTML = renderBacklinks(backlinks);
    }
  }
});
```
The drawback of this option is you cannot render the backlinks in the layouts. The advantage is that it's more universal because it doesn't depend on a specific template engine like markdown. It's compatible with mdx, jsx, etc.

The `slugify_urls` plugin [registers the `slugify` filter](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/main/plugins/slugify_urls.ts#L32), so you can use this function in your templates. For example:

```vto
{{ "Text to slugify" |> slugify }}
```

> However, `createSlugifier` is not currently exported as part of the public API.

In Lume there's no "private" API. If you need to create a different instance of the slugifier, you can simply import the module:

```js
import createSlugifier from "lume/core/slugifier.ts";

const slugifier = createSlugifier();
```

