Following the discussion in other issues, I've created a `_config.js` to run all js files through the Terser minifier:
````js
import lume from "https://deno.land/x/lume/mod.js";
import textLoader from "https://deno.land/x/lume/loaders/text.js";
import "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/terser/dist/bundle.min.js";

const site = lume({
  src: "lib",
  dest: "outlib",
  prettyUrls: false
});

site.loadAssets([".js"], textLoader);
site.process([".js"], processor);

async function processor (file) {
  let content = file.content;

  let opts = {
    module: true,
    compress: true,
    mangle: true
  };

  let output = await globalThis.Terser.minify(content, opts);

  file.content = output.code;
}

export default site;
````
I've not thorougly tested the output yet, but in principle it works well. It's not a 'static site' in the traditional sense, but is using Lume as a file processor to minify all files in `lib/` into `outlib/`. Like Denopack, it imports the browser version of Terser, which creates the Terser global. Specifying `globalThis` is not strictly necessary, but makes it clear where this Terser reference is coming from. 

So, I can either document this as an example of what can be done, or create a processor and/or plugin for general use. Another issue mentions passing options to plugins, and this would also be useful here, for example, whether to generate sourcemaps (the appropriate module would have to be imported to support this, of course).

Comments.Body:
Just been looking at producing a sourcemap, and this is more complicated than simply setting an option. You first have to `import "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/source-map@0.7.3/dist/source-map.js";`. Then you need the filename, and set that in the options so the links between the two can be created:
````
  let filename = file.src.path + file.src.ext;

  let opts = {
    module: true,
    compress: true,
    mangle: true,
    sourceMap: {
      filename: filename,
      url: filename + '.map'
    }
  };
````
and then you have to output 2 files for each input file. How can this be done in the processor function?

yes, that works well. As the processor has access to the site data, I think the simplest way to pass in options is to create a `_data` file in the directory with appropriate settings. The global references can be hidden in the `deps` file, which would `export { minify, MOZ_SourceMap }`, which could then be imported into the plugin as normal import refs.

So the code looks something like:
````js
site.loadAssets([".js"], textLoader);
site.process([".js"], processor);

async function processor(file) {
  let content = file.content;
  let filename = file.src.path + file.src.ext;

  let opts = {
    module: true,
    compress: true,
    mangle: true
  };

  if (file.fullData.sourceMap) {
    opts.sourceMap = {
      filename: filename,
      url: filename + '.map'
    }
  }

  let output = await minify(content, opts);

  file.content = output.code;

  if (output.map) {
    let mapFile = file.duplicate();
    mapFile.content = output.map;
    mapFile.dest.ext = ".js.map";
    site.pages.push(mapFile);
  }
}
````
Then default is not to produce a sourcemap, and have a `_data` file with `sourceMap: true` in the directory if you want them. Other options could be set in a separate `options` object in `_data`.

`_data` files shouldn't be used for configuration. We have `_config.js` for that.

If you create a plugin, it can accept an object with configuration values. The basic structure for a plugin is:

```js
export default function (options = {}) {
  return (site) => {
    // The plugin code
  };
}
```

You can see `css` plugin for a real example.

Doing so, in `_config.js` file, you can use the plugin and configure it:

```js
site.use(bundler({ map: true }));
```

> Is the aim not for processors and plugins to be independent?

No strong opinions here. Sometimes is more practical to have everything in a single file. For example, [markdown plugin](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/plugins/markdown.js) register the markdown template engine and create a filter to render markdown in any other template engine. Because we are using the same markdownIt instance, the filter is defined in the same file.

I have other filters like [url](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/filters/url.js) that are in its own file, but it requires access to the `site` instance, so it returns a function that returns another function, so [on register it](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/mod.js#L17) I can set the current site instance.

So my recomendation is that if you want to create the processor in a different file, don't export the processor directly but a function that return the processor. So you can set additional arguments (like options) needed for the processor. As an example:

```js
// processor.js
export default function (options) {
  return function (page, site) {
    //processor code
  }
}
```

```js
// plugin.js
import processor from "../processors/procesor.js";

export default function (options) {
  return function (site) {
    //Generate the processor with the custom options
    const fn = processor(options);

    //Register it
    site.process([".js"], fn);
  }
}
```

> in any case, _data files are already used for configuration: layout, for example.

IMHO they are different things. `layout`, `permalink` defines how a page must be rendered and saved. But sourcemaps is a global configuration, that even can depend on some environment. For example, you may want to generate sourcemaps only in dev mode.

I guess this is a matter of taste and Lume is flexible enough to allow to make all these things.
I prefer to have configurations options separated from data of website. Note also that you can store config data in the `site` instance, like other configuration values like `src`, `dest` or `prettyUrls`. For example:

```js
const site = lume({
  src: "src",
  dest: "dist",
  terser: {
    module: true,
    compress: true,
    mangle: true
  }
});

const terserOpts = site.options.terser;
```

@probins Thinking more about this, I going to change a bit the options structure for this plugin, in order to make it consistent with other plugins. In `css` (that probably I'll rename it to `postcss`) we have two options: 

```js
site.use(css({
    postcssPlugins: [], //Array of plugins
    map: true
}))
```

I think plugins shouldn't use the exact options object passed to the library, because this closes the door to other options specific to Lume. So I think terser should be:

```js
site.use(terser({
    options: {
        module: true,
        compress: true,
        mangle: true,
    },
    map: true
}))
```

Doing so, we can expand this object with more values for lume (for example: other file extensions, transpile typescript, etc).

Yes, you have to create a page in javascript or typescript exporting a generator. You have an example with pagination here: https://lumeland.github.io/creating-pages/pagination/

Basically, every value returned by a generator will be converted to a page. The 11ty example would be something like this:

```js
// possum-pages.tmpl.js

export default function *({possums}) {
    for (const possum of possums) {
        yield {
            permalink: `possums/${possum.name}/`,
            content: `${possum.name} is ${possum.age} years old`
        }
    }
}
```

I have been playing the with deno-image (https://github.com/MariusVatasoiu/deno-image) package and I think it can be used for a first version of this plugin, until sharp is available for Deno.

It's a very limited package, because it supports jpg and png formats and only can resize them, but it could be useful in some cases. I couldn't find any other Deno package with better results (https://deno.land/x?query=image)

[ImageScript](https://deno.land/x/imagescript@1.1.19) looks great but it only supports nearest neighbor scaling mode, so the output has poor quality.

The WIP plugin is here: https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/master/plugins/image.js and the way to use it is:

```js
site.use(image({
  resize: {
    "/img/avatars": {
      "-small": { width: 100, height: 100 },
      "-medium": { width: 500, height: 500 },
      "-big": { width: 1000, height: 1000 }
    },
    "/img/pictures/*.jpg": {
      "-mobile": { width: 500, height: 500 },
      "-tablet": { width: 1000, height: 1000 },
      "-desktop": { width: 1500, height: 1500 }
    }
  }
}));
```

The plugin take all images of `/img/avatars` folder and create three versions appending the suffix `-small`, `-medium` and `-big` to the new versions. You can use also glob patterns, as you can see in the second example `/img/pictures/*.jpg`.

@enjikaka 
- It uses `loadAssets` to load the image files, so they are pages that can be (pre)processed.
- The processor looks for the `imagick` value [here](https://github.com/lumeland/experimental-plugins/blob/main/imagick/imagick.ts#L36)
- If this value doesn't exist, do nothing. If exists, execute it.
- It returns an object with filenames as keys and transform functions as values. For example:
  ```js
  {
    "/filename.jpg": (img) => img.resize(200, 200),
    "/filename-small.jpg": (img) => img.resize(100, 100),
    "/filename-big.jpg": (img) => img.resize(300, 300),
  }
  ```
- It generates new files for every entry of this object, using the ImageMagick API to transform the original image.
- In the demo, I've used a `_data.ts` file to apply the same function to all files of a directory. This allows to assign different functions to files in different directories.
- Due the function is assigned like any other regular `data` variable, you can use _data files or use other processor to set this value automatically. For example, to resize all jpg files, you can assign the function with this processor:
  ```js
  site.process([".jpg", (file) => {
      file.data.imagick = function (url) {
        return {
          [url]: (img) => img.resize(150, 150)
        }
      };
  });
- This opens the door to create other plugins that can generate the imagick functions automatically, for example, by scanning the images in the HTML and parsing special attributes.

