This issue should be in the main Lume repo, due this repo is only for the documentation site. I just transfered it to the right repo :)

Thanks for bringing this up. I think the markdown plugin should have a `rules` option, so you can define them in this way:

```js
const markdown = {
    pugins: [footnote],
    rules: {
        footnote_block_open: () => (
          "<h2>This is a custom footnote header</h2>\n" +
          '<section class="footnotes">\n' +
          '<ol class="footnotes-list">\n'
        )
    }
}

const site = lume({ markdown });
```

I'll add this option, thanks!


Meanwhile, you can recover the existing markdown engine as following (so no need to create a new engine):

```js
const site = lume();

const mdEngine = site.formats.get(".md").engine;
```

@naiyerasif would be awesome if you had time to look into this issue and maybe implement the solution @oscarotero suggested yesterday in the help channel:

> The only solution I can think is store the data in a sub-key
> instead of store the data in the root of the page (page.data.toc) 
> it should be stored in a predefined key, like page.data.vfile.toc)

Here is the rehypeExtractExcerpt plugin maybe you can additionally use for testing/recreation:

```typescript
import { hastUtilToString, unified, unistUtilVisit } from "../deps.ts";

export interface RehypeExtractExcerptOptions {
  /** The var name of the vFile.data export. defaults to `excerpt` */
  name?: string;

  /** The character length to truncate the excerpt. defaults to 140  */
  maxLength?: number;

  /** The ellipsis to add to the excerpt. defaults to `...` */
  ellipsis?: string;

  /** Truncate the excerpt at word boundary. defaults to `true` */
  wordBoundaries?: boolean;
}

const defaults: RehypeExtractExcerptOptions = {
  name: "excerpt",
  maxLength: 140,
  ellipsis: "...",
  wordBoundaries: true,
};

const rehypeExtractExcerpt: unified.Plugin<
  [RehypeExtractExcerptOptions?],
  hastUtilToString.Root,
  void
> = (userOptions?: RehypeExtractExcerptOptions) => {
  const options = { ...defaults, ...userOptions };

  return (tree: hastUtilToString.Root, vfile: unified.VFileWithOutput<unknown>) => {
    const excerpt: string[] = [];

    unistUtilVisit.visit(tree, "element", (node: hastUtilToString.Element) => {
      if (node.tagName !== "p") {
        return;
      }

      excerpt.push(
        truncateExcerpt(
          hastUtilToString.toString(node),
          options.maxLength!,
          options.ellipsis!,
          options.wordBoundaries!,
        ),
      );

      return unistUtilVisit.EXIT;
    });

    vfile.data[options.name!] = excerpt[0];
  };
};

function truncateExcerpt(
  str: string,
  maxLength: number,
  ellipsis: string,
  wordBoundaries: boolean,
): string {
  if (str.length > maxLength) {
    if (wordBoundaries) {
      return `${str.slice(0, str.lastIndexOf(" ", maxLength - 1))}${ellipsis}`;
    }
    return `${str.slice(0, maxLength)}${ellipsis}`;
  }
  return str;
}

export default rehypeExtractExcerpt;
```

1319682994.Body:
Since `<!DOCTYPE html>` is not valid JSX, but [must be included](https://html.com/tags/doctype/) in `.html` documents for best practices, I suggest adding a feature to automatically add `<!DOCTYPE html>`, to the JSX plugins. [Some more info on stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48653734/react-server-side-rendering-invariant-violation-invalid-tag-doctype-html).

This can be implemented easily with the snippet taken from the [source code](https://github.com/fabon-f/website/blob/master/_config.js) of the lume showcase website [fabon.info](https://www.fabon.info/):

```js
/** Register the plugin to support JSX and TSX files */
export default function (userOptions?: Partial<Options>) {
  const options = merge(defaults, userOptions);
  const extensions = Array.isArray(options.extensions)
    ? { pages: options.extensions, components: options.extensions }
    : options.extensions;

  return (site: Site) => {
    const engine = new PreactJsxEngine();

    site.loadPages(extensions.pages, loader, engine);
    site.loadComponents(extensions.components, loader, engine);
    site.process([".html"], addDoctype)

    function addDoctype(page: Page) {
      if (!page.content?.toString().trim().startsWith("<!DOCTYPE")) {
        page.content = `<!DOCTYPE html>${page.content}`;
      }
    }
  };
}
```

@oscarotero if this is cool for you, let me know and I will create a PR for the JSX plugins.

