  const slug = page.src.slug;

  return `./${date}-${slug}.html`;
};
```

In this example, the output is a relative url, so if the page is in a subdirectory, like `/blog/`, the path is automatically prepended.
It returns the url including the `.html` extension. The `modifyUrls` plugin can be used to remove the extension in the links in the HTML code, but internally, the urls of the pages must include this extension to work properly. It's used to identify this page as HTML, so it can be detected by other plugins that work with HTML pages (for example to minify, apply some DOM modifications, etc).

