Yes, my example was very exaggerated. Other more common example is if you don't want to have pretty urls for a specific file. For example, it's common the page to show in case of 404 errors is `404.html`, so you can create this page with `404.html.md`.

Anyway, the thing is it's easier to simply say "If the filename contains an extension, it's used as the output extension, otherwise, the html extension is used". 

If you have to add "...except for some extensions like md or pug that are formats intended to output html, so the extension in the filename will be ignored", this introduces some cognitive load in how Lume works and make its behavior less predictable.

Maybe is this a bad design choice? Perhaps, I don't know. To me, a file shouldn't have a dot in the name, because this is introduces some ambiguity. You can request the url `/foo/bar.png` expecting a png file but it opens the html page `/foo/bar.png/index.html`.

Anyway, keep in mind that this is the default way to generate url by Lume. If you want to change this behavior, it's very easy: just [create a `url` function](https://lume.land/docs/creating-pages/urls/#urls-as-functions) in the `/_data.js` file with your own implementation. For example:

```js
export function url (page) {
  return `./${page.src.slug}/`;
}
```

