Comments.Body:
This is not a bug, but is how Deno works.
Any module loaded with `import ...` is cached by Deno and there's no way to refresh the module after any change.

This is why Lume exposes the `comp` variable:

```js
// default.tmpl.ts

import { PageData } from "lume/core.ts";

export default (data: PageData) => {
  const { comp } = data;

  return /*html*/ `<html>
  ${comp.head(data)}
  <body>
    ${comp.body(data)}
  </body>
</html>`;
};
```

More info: https://lume.land/docs/core/components/

Thanks for the information, at first it did not work because I used the same extension for the components as for the templates. 

- _components/head.tmpl.ts";
- _components/body.tmpl.ts";

now using 
- _components/head.ts";
- _components/body.ts";

It works like a charm.

To import files relative to the current file, use relative paths (starting with dot):

```css
@import "./reset.css";
@import "./navbar.css";
```

Note that Lume will load and process all css files found in the src directory, so you will have not only the `styles.css` files but also the `reset.css` and `navbar.css` files in the dest folder. That's why they are placed in the `_includes` folder. because it's ignored due it starts with `_`. You can [ignore the other files](https://lume.land/docs/configuration/ignore-files/) with this function:

```js
// Ignore all css files but "styles.css"
site.ignore((path) => path.endsWith(".css") && path !== "/styles.css");
```

